Champions access the dashboard via desktop/laptop
devices as behaviourally the tasks are the types of tasks
they would always do this way. Having presented our
findings to Dementia Friends, we decided to
focus our
design on desktop/laptop, not mobile, but with a
responsive focus.
Device Usage
9/11 Champions complete all of their tasks on a
desktop/laptop. Champions take their role very seriously,
and want to make sure they complete their tasks
properly, associating mobile with making mistakes and
not giving full concentration to the task in hand.
Findings
Takeaways
The Global Navigation on the current site is detrimental to
the user experience of the Champions. We presented our
findings to the Dementia Friends developer and it was
agreed that we could
design for a microsite.
Global Navigation
The current dashboard sat within the wider Dementia
Friends site. Champions were confused by the Global
Navigation which was aimed at the main site and not
the dashboard.
With the validation of the top features,
we could give
hierarchy to the Global Navigation and could make them
main Call-To-Actions on the homepage.
Feature Prioritization
By asking Champions to sort a list of the dashboards
features into a prioritised order, we validated the list that
Dementia Friends had given us.
Champions see
Creating, Reporting, Ordering Materials and
Downloading Resources as their main tasks. They saw
the rest as superfluous.
With over 110 resources, this section would require some
strong Information Architecture. We ran a card sorting to
give understanding of how we might structure this section,
but no patterns emerged, emphasizing the extensive nature
of the resources.
Finding Session Resources
Champions believe the resources are very good but find
it extremely difficult to navigate through them. This
causes great frustration.
This situation can be reminded by a simpler, better
structured dashboard. However, if they need
the contact
details of their DFO, these need to be readily available for
them to ease the process.
Assistance from Dementia Friends Officers (DFO)
When Champions got stuck on their tasks, their first
action was to get in touch with their DFO to ask for
help, increasing their work load.
